				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: what are bards really for..<a name="26752"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 10 04 1:54 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Patience, young bard.  There are some interesting things in store for you very soon.  The key to understanding what lies ahead is to carefully review the songs we receive:
<br />

<br />
Level 5: Selo's.  This is the defining song.  Get a good drum.  Your speed increases as you level.
<br />

<br />
Level 8 song:  Learn to use it to split mobs for pulling.  It even works in dungeons!
<br />

<br />
Level 15 song: The beginnings of your career in Crowd Control are now in place.  Learn to crowd control and pull and you will rarely be without a group as your reputation grows.
<br />

<br />
Level 19: Invisibility song.
<br />

<br />
Read the guides to pulling and crowd control on EqDiva.  
<br />

<br />
The 20s: Slowing mob attack speeds, controlling runners with snare, fear, damage shields, higher mezz, resist psalms and the first charm song!  Things are getting exciting now.  If you are into soloing . . . 
<br />

<br />
The 30s: The Chants.  Higher level charm, better mana/health regeneration songs, and bind sight (this one will be a great help throughout your pulling career).
<br />

<br />
The 40s and beyond:  It just all gets better.
<br />

<br />
When I started, the 20s were particularly difficult as we didn't really have the benefit if the current level 8 and 15 songs.  However, when I play alts, I now see 20's bards in places such as Paludal Caverns and Highkeep, pulling and controlling adds while doing all the other things bards can do. 
<br />

<br />
Good luck and stop by often.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
